The Saxona behaved with reat gallantry, and, having sustained the assaults of the Egritons, forced them to fly3 and upon this advantage pursued them with slaughter to the mountain Damon, which was as long as they could do it with day-light. The moun· tain was high, and had a hazel-wood upon the top os it, and about the middle broken and cavernous rocks, which were a barbour to wild heasts. The Britons made up to it, and stayed there all night among the rocks and hezel-bushes. But as it began to draw towards day, Uther commanded the consuls and princes to be called together, that he might con· sult with them in what manner to assault the enemy.
